fields.info:
Lap swimming is open to all participants 13 yrs+ interested in swimming for fitness.




No more reservations required! Either buy your pass online through our CivicRec site or in
                        person at the pool!




(NOTE: When there 2+ swimmers per lane, swimmers must "circle swim" by swimming down the right
                        side of the lane at all times - like driving in the USA)

Our recreational swim is open to swimmers of all ages for Burlingame and non-Burlingame
                                residents alike!


Participants are welcome to bring balls, floats, and other toys (excluding water guns,
                                launchers, etc.) to use to have fun in the pool!



We ask that non-potty trained children wear a swim diaper to keep our pool nice and
                                clean!

Water aerobics classes are a great way to exercise, meet new friends, and change up your
                            regular routine. Our dedicated aquatic fitness staff teaches to every experience level.
                            And, our slate of Aqua Fitness programs covers a wide range of skills and needs,
                            with paces and class formats that vary depending on the program you select.



                            Join us for a great late morning break! This medium-to-high intensity aerobics class uses
                            bands, water weights, and noodles for cardiovascular (aerobic) exercise,
                            as well as strength training, toning, and stretching.

fields.philosophy:
Our swim lesson program starts with safety and comfort in the water,
                        giving each swimmer, of all ages, a strong foundation of skills that support development
                        into a competent or even competitive-level swimmer and foster a love of swimming that will last
                        a
                        lifetime.








   We provide Private Lessons for those who seek the extra guidance.
fields.registration_info:
To register for our classes, please follow these steps:

  1. Review the Class Descriptions on the page you will find at the link below to identify the level(s) best for you and your family
  2. Select the best dates/times for the level(s) you need; note the activity numbers for the classes that you have selected
  3. Create an account with CivicRec if you need to! This will be where you see available classes, waitlists, add family members, and can make payments.
  4. Use the links on the schedule pages to connect to our registration system, using the activity numbers to locate your desired classes
fields.waitlist_info:
• IF YOUR LESSON IS FULL, MAKE SURE TO ENROLL INTO THE WAIT LIST! We often make new classes with long waitlists on them so don't miss out!

  • If you would like to sign up for classes AFTER the start date, you can do so until 10 PM on the day of the second class

    (i.e. M/W classes, registration will close the first Wednesday of the session at 10 PM)

    HOWEVER you will still be responsible for paying the FULL amount of the class. This is to support the cost of our staff and pool upkeep and we CANNOT give credits or refunds for classes missed due to late registration.
fields.policy:
If you wish to cancel a group lesson, you must do so 24 hours before the start of the first class to receive a full refund. After a class has begun, refunds and credits will not be given. Make-ups are not available for missed classes.

Lessons are held rain or shine, although they will be canceled if there is thunder and/or lightning. We reserve the right to cancel or postpone any program or activity due to low enrollment.

fields.small_pool_one_description: his is a fun, friendly, introductory class for a parent and their infant to get used to the water! This is meant to be a childâ€™s first experience getting in the water/pool and how as parents to work (and play!) with your child in an aquatic environment. We ask that if your child is not potty trained that you wear a water dipper while in the pool.
fields.small_pool_two_description: Preschool 1 is for children who are new to swimming! If they have never been in the pool, this is a great place to start. They will learn how to be comfortable in the water and learn the basic swimming skills. By the end of the class, they will be able to: Enter/exit pool using ladder, blow bubbles (mouth/nose), open eyes underwater, roll front/back w/ assistance, jump off side, submerge completely, starfish/monkey/airplane float for 10s unassisted, kick on front/backside (w/instructor), head in water, side breathing (face turns to side, ear in water).
fields.small_pool_three_description: Preschool 2 focuses a bit more on teaching the basic ideas of freestyle and backstroke to give your children a good idea of how to swim for longer periods of time. Note that this class is often repeated many times! A lot of fundamentals are learned here! It is always a good idea to make sure your child is very very comfortable with these techniques before moving them on. By the end of the class, they will be able to: Side breathing (freestyle), flutter kick (front/back sides) for two pool lengths, surface dive (retrieve object from bottom), demonstrate streamline guide, demonstrate freestyle (one pool length), demonstrate backstroke (one pool length).
fields.small_pool_four_description: This is a class for children that have had previous swimming experience before. They need to be comfortable swimming in the pool (at least one length) and doing water activities that include putting their head underwater. It is recommended that they complete our Preschool 2 class to make sure they are the best prepared! By the end of the class, they will be able to: Swim three pool lengths (freestyle/backstroke) comfortably, swim one pool length of breaststroke comfortably, execute two pool lengths of dolphin kick with ease, perform a 5-yard streamlined push-off from the wall, and demonstrate butterfly arms and kick proficiency.
fields.big_pool_one_description: Barracuda 1 is a class for children new to swimming who are above the age of five! This is designed to get the children used to water activities who have had little to no swimming experience. They will learn the basic fundamentals of swimming and be comfortable in the water. By the end of the class, they will be able to: Enter/exit water with ladder, blow bubbles (nose/mouth), open eyes underwater, retrieve submerged objects, roll front to back and back to front with assistance, jump off side, submerge completely, starfish/monkey/airplane float for 10s unassisted, kick on front/backside (w/instructor, one pool length), place head in water, side breathing (face turns to side, ear in water), swim one length freestyle/backstroke with kick stick assistance, lifeguard recognition.
fields.big_pool_two_description: Barracuda 2 is for children that are ready to learn more stroke work and become more comfortable in the pool but still donâ€™t have a lot of experience with swimming. Recommended you take our Barracuda 1 class if you are worried about their ability level! In this class they will learn more about the techniques and mechanics of the strokes and how to become comfortable swimming them! Focuses on freestyle and backstroke. By the end of the class, they will be able to: Side breathe (freestyle), independent front/back float (20s), glide two body lengths independently (push off wall), glide and recover to vertical position, comfortable kicking two lengths (freestyle/backstroke), comfortably swim two straight lengths (backstroke), comfortably swim two lengths (freestyle, side breathing).
fields.big_pool_three_description: Barracuda 3 is a class for children who are confident in the water! They should be able to swim at least a few lengths of the pool and be comfortable putting their head underwater along. Knowledge of basic stroke techniques are recommended and they need to be able to demonstrate two lengths of continuous swimming (using strokes). This is a class to develop their skills, improve their swimming endurance, and give them more stroke techniques. By the end of the class, they will be able to: Comfortably swim three lengths of the pool (freestyle/backstroke), one length of breaststroke, two lengths of dolphin kick, push off wall into a 5-yard streamlined glide, demonstrate butterfly arms and kick.
fields.big_pool_four_description: Barracuda 4 is for children who are very comfortable in the water. They know different strokes, can swim multiple lengths of the pool, and have advanced water skills. This will prepare your children for going onto Pre-Team and more advanced swimming classes. We highly recommend you make sure your child is a comfortable swimmer! As a note, children will NOT be able to move onto Pre-Team, Gators, etc. if they do not first pass this class. By the end of the class, they will be able to: Open turns (all four strokes), two-handed touch (butterfly and breaststroke), one-handed touch (freestyle and backstroke), understanding of backstroke flags, tread water for 1.5 minutes, comfortable swimming 75 yards (all four strokes), underwater push-off from the wall into a streamlined position, clear understanding of 5-10 seconds apart intervals, clear understanding of circle swimming.
fields.big_pool_five_description: *REQUIREMENT* Child must have either passed Barracuda 4 OR be able to swim 100 meters of both freestyle and backstroke and 25 meters of both breaststroke and butterfly. Pre-Team is a class meant to prepare your child for competitive swimming! They will focus on refining their swimming skills, learn how to swim in a competition setting, and get a feel for what the training regiment will be like. They will learn key swim team skills such as: reading the pace clock, training intervals, and knowing competition rules.
fields.big_pool_six_description: Gators is a class for pre-teen and teen children who are new to technical swimming or new to BACâ€™s swimming programs. It is not expected that children be familiar with the technical fundamentals of swimming strokes before they start this class, however the curriculum is adaptable to the ability level of the children in each session. All four strokes are taught/learned/improved in this class to get them ready to go onto a more difficult level of swimming, typically a team. If youâ€™re child is trying to improve their swimming ability to be at a competitive level, it is common to repeat this class a few times until they are ready!

fields.lesson1_description:
Private Lessons are held in a 1 to 1 ratio of instructor to student. Students come in
                        with a stated level and work with the instructor to improve their skills.
                    Private lesson sessions are 30 minutes and cost $60 per session.
fields.lesson2_description:
Semi-Private Lessons are held in a 1 to 2 ratio of instructor to students. Lessons are
                        tailored to the specific needs of the students and create a fun learning environment.

                    Semi-Private lesson sessions are 30 minutes and cost $80 per session.
fields.philosophy_info:
Need a little extra help? Improve your skills with private lessons and take your
                            swimming to the next level. We offer both Private and Semi-Private Lessons
                            year-round.
fields.policy_info:
Cancellations must be made 24 hours before the first class for a full refund.
Lessons are held rain or shine, canceled only in case of thunder and/or lightning.

fields.philosophy:
BAC's Masters Swimming Program offers high-quality training for adults of all skill levels,
                        from beginners to experienced athletes like triathletes, former Olympians, and college
                        champions.
                        The program welcomes anyone interested in organized swim workouts, regardless of their mastery
                        level.
                        Coached sessions provide both aerobic exercise and stroke technique improvement,
                        with access to long course training giving an added advantage.
                        The team fosters a strong sense of camaraderie, supporting and motivating each other
                        to succeed in both local and out-of-state events.
                        Whether pursuing personal bests, triathlons, or fitness,
                        BAC's Masters Swimming Program provides a welcoming environment for all.
fields.registration: To participate in BAC's Masters Swimming program, all swimmers are required to be active members of US Masters Swimming (USMS). Proof of USMS membership is necessary before starting training, regardless of being a pass-holder or drop-in participant. Membership needs to be renewed annually at the beginning of each calendar year. To register for the Masters program, individuals should send a copy of their current USMS membership to davidspitzler@yahoo.com.

fields.philosophy:
BAC offers a competitive Masters water polo program for individuals aged 18 and above,
                        known as Burlingame Master's Water Polo. The program is designed for experienced players,
                        many of whom have college-level water polo experience.
                        Proficiency in the game and swimming at the team's pace are expected.


                        Since this program maintains a high level of play, players are required to undergo
                        a tryout and consultation with coaches to assess their suitability for the program.
                        The priority is to ensure a safe and suitable environment for both new and existing
                        players. The group occasionally participates in tournaments, including major events
                        like US Masters Nationals and local Pacific Zone League competitions.
                        However, such tournament participation involves additional costs and is not organized
                        by BAC.
fields.schedule_notes:
ALL NEW PLAYERS MUST CONTACT THE COACHES PRIOR TO COMING
                        TO PRACTICE AND GETTING IN THE POOL (email Peter Jacobs)

                        NO MORE DROP-INS ON TUESDAYS AND THURSDAYS

fields.practiceNotes_two:
A poll for Saturdsay pratice is sent out Friday morning to confirm sufficient attendance
                                to

fields.practiceNotes_three: In order to get added to the Google Groups email list that includes practice polls, updates on time changes, holidays, etc., please contact group leader Peter Jacobs.
fields.registration: To join the Burlingame Masters Water Polo Club, individuals need to be registered as drop-in athletes, monthly members, or quarterly members. Monthly membership offers unlimited practice access starting from any date. Drop-in athletes are required to pay a fee before each practice session to participate in the water polo activities.

fields.description:
Ben came to BAC in 2014 after many years as an athlete and a coach in the Bay Area.  Ben grew up swimming in Los Altos for Los Altos-Mountain View Aquatic Club and for Los Altos High School, where making CCS Finals was a highlight of his prep career.  After moving to Palo Alto Swim Club (now part of PASA) for his senior year in high school, Ben attended Vassar College, where he was a 4-year varsity swim team member, 3-year captain, and 9-time school record holder.

Upon completing his degree in Sociology with minors in American Literature and French from Vassar in 2003, Ben began his coaching career back in the Bay Area.  Ben has guided multiple athletes who have broken Pacific Age Group Records, have placed in the National Top-10, have made finals at USA Swimming Junior Nationals, and who have earned accolades on local, national and international levels.  Athletes that Ben has coached have gone on to represent Team USA at international competitions and have gone on to become NCAA All-Americans. 

Ben is active on the Zone, LSC and National levels, having previously served as a Zone All-Star coach, a Pacific All-Star coach and Pacific Camp Coach. In 2018, Ben was named to the staff of the USA Swimming National Diversity Select Camp as an assistant coach, a true honor and highlight of his career. In 2020, Ben was appointed to the Western Zone Select Camp staff.

One of the underlying emphases of Benâ€™s coaching philosophy is that swimming can help open the door for athletes to new experiences and to an enhanced academic profile.  Athletes that Ben has coached have gone on to swim at many of the countryâ€™s best colleges and universities, including UC-Berkeley, UCLA, Stanford, USC, Harvard, Princeton, Brown, UPenn, Duke University, Northwestern University, Georgia Technical Institute, Amherst College, Washington University in St. Louis, and Harvey Mudd College, among others.  Ben is committed to developing the student-athlete here on the BAC pool deck.

Daniel started in Pacific Swimming, as a swimmer at 8 years old.
After competing all the way through elementary and middle school,
he decided to take his passion and educate our youth in water
safety. At 13 years old he started off volunteering for his swim
team during the summer, teaching his teammates younger siblings how
to swim, correcting stroke and preparing 8 and unders to swim
competitively. At 16 Daniel worked as a swim instructor and
lifeguard, while helping re-start the swim schools
â€œPre-Competitiveâ€ Swim
Team. 


Taking a break away from the pool and chlorine, Daniel started
working with students with Autism. He got his Registered Behavioral
Technician certificate and learned about the cause of different
behaviors. He learned techniques that can be directly translated to
coaching on deck. 


Most recently Daniel joined BACâ€™s fulltime coaching staff in
Sept 2021, after coaching for Piedmont Swim Team before Covid-19.
He has been selected as a Pacific Swimming All-Star Coach in Zone
2, has coached swimmers to multiple Junior Olympics and Far
Westerns and is a member of ASCA. 


Currently Coach Daniel is taking Kinesiology classes at College of
San Mateo. He is striving to complete a Kinesiology Degree as well
as his Athletic Coaching Certificate from College of San
Mateo.

After 12 years of coaching in the Bay Area, Golda came to BAC in
November 2020. Golda grew up swimming in Ft Lauderdale, FL. She
swam on teams such as FLST at the International Swimming Hall of
Fame, Broward Aquatics, and Brandon Blue Wave. During her time on
FLST, Golda became a part of 5 nationally top 16
relays. 


Her time at Broward Aquatics and Brandon Blue Wave led to some of
her highest athletic achievements.


In 2001, Golda competed in her first international competition for
her native country of El Salvador, winning 7 gold and 2 silver
medals, at the Central American Games in Guatemala. In 2002 she won
3 bronze in her speciality events, the 200, 400, and 800 meter
freestyles at the Central American and Caribbean Games in the
Dominican Republic. In 2006, at the Central American and Caribbean
Games in Cartagena, COL, she won 2 golds in the 400 and 800 meter
freestyles. Finally, in 2007, competing for the final time in El
Salvador at a meet called CCCAN, she won 3 golds (200, 400, 800)
and one silver (200 fly).


Golda was selected by her country to compete in 3 World
Championships: 2003 in Barcelona, 2007 in Melbourne, and 2008 in
Manchester. In 2007 she competed in the Pan American Games in
Brasil, where she was a part of her countryâ€™s 800 meter
freestyle relay, which placed 7th. It was the first time in El
Salvadorâ€™s history that a relay placed in the top 8
internationally. 


But Goldaâ€™s biggest honor and greatest achievement was
competing in the 2004 Olympics in Athens and the 2008 Olympics in
Beijing. 


It was after competing for 4 years at Florida State University,
graduating with a BA in English (Creative Writing) and completing
her MFA at National University, with a degree in English (Creative
Writing), Golda moved out to the Bay Area to pursue a coaching
career. 


Golda has coached many 10&unders, and have guided them to meets
such as JOs and Far Westerns, and has had one athlete selected for
the Western Zone All Star Team. Since joining BAC, Golda has
branched out, learning how to coach athletes at a Senior level, as
well as prepping them and getting them ready for
college. 


Goldaâ€™s swimming philosophy can also mirror her lifeâ€™s
philosophy: never be afraid to dream big. Golda is committed to
helping her BAC athletes achieve their dreams at their highest
level of potential.

Coach Hondorf was destined to be a pool rat from the moment his parents met as swimmers at The Johns Hopkins University. With two parents that would teach and coach, Loki developed a second nature with swimming analytics. Stuck on the pool deck for much longer than what would be considered "healthy", swimming and what the sport embodies became ingrained into Him.
 
Though Loki would initially despise the sport, vowing to quit when allowed. The hard work and reward therein would eventually transform him. Through his high school career at Oak Ridge H.S. in Tennessee Hondorf would continue to develop physically as a swimmer, but also as a coach. Beginning to help coach, as his Coaches (parents) continued to teach him about swimming.
 
Following 4 record breaking years at ORHS, Coach Hondorf would go on to set team records at the Colorado School of Mines en route to qualifying for and ultimately competing in NCAA nationals. After a fulfilling career, Coach Hondorf attempted, and ultimately failed, to retire from the pool deck completely. Soon after graduating Loki found work with the age group program for Foothills Swim Team, before again turning his gaze west yet again.
 
Having traveled across the country as a swimmer, Coach Loki has had the privilege of interacting with many figure heads of the sport and learning from many schools of thought. Coach Hondorf has continued to learn and grow both as a Coach and as a human, and he hopes that by guiding young athletes through their career he may give back just a fraction of what this sport has afforded him.

Sam grew up swimming competitively, coaching, and teaching swim lessons here on the Peninsula. She swam competitively for 12 years, after joining her first swim team at 8 years old.
 
After undergrad, Sam took a step away from the swimming community to pursue education. Sam has a Masters in Education with a focus on Childhood Development. She taught 1st, 2nd, and 3rd grade locally. Sam has a Masters in Education with a focus on Childhood Development. 
 
Now, Sam works for an Educational Technology company that provides a Transition Curriculum that supports Middle and High School Special Education programs. With this new career change, she has decided it is time to get reinvolved with the swimming community and is ultimately extremely excited to get back on the pool deck in the afternoons and work with Barracuda I & II going forward.

Tommy joined BAC in April 2023. Tommy started his swimming career as a summer leaguer in Lafayette at Rancho Colorados when he was 6 and continued until 14. In High School, Tommy joined Orinda Aquatics and found success in the mid-distance events qualifying for Junior Nationals in 200/500 Free, 200/400 IM, and 200 Fly. While swimming with OA, Tommy got his first coaching experience working with the 6&Unders, 7-8s and 9-10s at his old summer league team. After high school, Tommy continued swimming at Cal-Berkeley for 3 years where he was a part of two National Championship Teams in 2011 & 2012. 

 

Following the conclusion of Tommyâ€™s swimming career, he was recruited by a former Cal teammate to join the coaching staff at The Olympic Club. Between 2014 and 2019, Tommy had the opportunity to work with swimmers of all ages and abilities, from 8 year olds preparing for their first meets, to Junior Olympic (AGCâ€™s) and Far Western High Point award winners, to Sectionals, Futures and Junior Nationalist qualifiers/finalists. TOC swimmers under Tommy have set Pacific Records, ranked in the top 10 nationally and gone on to swim at colleges including Cal, UCLA, Brown, West Point, Kenyon, Wesleyan, Colgate, and Carnegie Mellon. Tommy emphasizes teamwork and celebrating each success as an accomplishment of the group. Swimming is a challenging sport and our teammates supporting each other is critical for sustained success. 

 

In addition to working with the 18&Under team, Tommy also ran workouts for The Olympic Club Masters team, again working with a wide range of ages and abilities running from post collegiate athletes to swimmers still competing at 95+ years of age. Coach Tommy oversaw a small post collegiate group of 7 swimmers that competed at the 2016 Olympic Trials in Omaha. While at The Olympic Club, Tommy was twice nominated for the ASCA Age Group coach of the year award based on the teamâ€™s results in the 12&Under age groups. Tommy left The Olympic Club in 2019 as the Head Coach of the Swim Team to return to UC Berkeley to finish his Bachelorâ€™s degree in Data Science. 

 

During Covid Tommy returned to the water as a masterâ€™s swimmer. Since 2021, almost 10 years after his last college meet, Tommy has competed at Masters Nationals, raced several Open water races and completed a relay crossing of the North Channel between Scotland and Ireland in a World Record Time. He is excited to help BAC swimmers set goals of every level and find a lifelong love of swimming. Tommy believes that there are many ways to swim fast, and his most important role as a coach is to provide his swimmers with the tools and knowledge to best achieve their own success.

Our competitive swim team programs is to cultivate a nurturing and competitive environment where young swimmers can excel both in the pool and in life. We are committed to fostering personal growth, discipline, teamwork, and resilience in our athletes. With a focus on technique, fitness, and sportsmanship, we aim to develop well-rounded individuals who embrace challenges and celebrate achievements. Through dedication, guidance, and a passion for swimming, we aspire to shape not only exceptional athletes but also confident leaders ready to make waves in the pool and beyond.

fields.description:
The Burlingame Aquatic Club (BAC) mission is to serve our community by providing excellent aquatic
                    opportunities. We believe there is a place in aquatics for everyone. We strive to make this belief a
                    reality for anyone who walks through our doors. BAC was founded in 2000 to focus on competitive
                    aquatics for youth and adults, with very successful programs in Club Swimming (USS), Masters
                    Swimming (USMS), Masters Water Polo and Club Water Polo (USWP). Many of our athletes achieved
                    notable success on a national level. Beginning in 2011, BAC began managing all community and
                    competitive programs (except high school athletics) on behalf of the City of Burlingame. Our
                    programs expanded to include programs such as open swim, swim lessons, summer camps, adult aerobics
                    and community events. Our goals are to facilitate growth and development at all skill levels for
                    athletes of all ages from 6 months. As a nonprofit organization, we have very strong loyalty to our
                    community, our neighbors, and all of the families who participate in our programs. The main aquatic
                    center we utilize is owned by the San Mateo Union High School District (SMUHSD) and is located on
                    the campus of Burlingame High School. We work in close collaboration with the City of Burlingameâ€™s
                    Parks & Recreation Department. Our 50m pool ranges from 3-13 feet and accommodates lap and
                    recreational swimming. The wading/instructional pool is 3.5 feet. The Executive Director (ED)
                    reports to the Board of Directors and manages all aspects of the BAC.
